<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910311-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>910311-0044.</DOCID><HL>   Earnings of Citicorp's Reed   Decreased 22% Last Year</HL><DATE>03/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   CCI FNB</CO><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)BANKS (BNK)</IN><LP>   Citicorp Chairman John Reed's earnings fell more than$300,000 last year to $1.2 million as disappointing profitled the largest U.S. banking company to freeze salaries andpay no bonuses to senior executives.   Mr. Reed's compensation represented a 22% decline from1989, when he took a cut of about $250,000 from the previousyear. The figures are contained in the company's proxystatement mailed to shareholders late last week. Thestatement showed that the 39-person senior management groupreceived total cash compensation of $18,285,000 in 1990,roughly 10% less than the year earlier.</LP><TEXT>   The no bonus rule was also in affect at First ChicagoCorp., another major banking company whose earnings were hurtby problem loans. But there the impact of the new policy wasgreater. According to the company's proxy statement, ChairmanBarry Sullivan received a salary of $736,000, a $50,000increase from the previous year. But he gave up his incentivecompensation, which totaled an additional $775,000 in 1989.Mr. Sullivan and President Richard Thomas, who had a $500,000incentive compensation in 1989, had recommended that FirstChicago's Management Council of 23 top executives forgobonuses in 1990.</TEXT></DOC>